text: our government. we have been fooled. we grew up being told that our founding father‚Äôs were so incredibly smart that they built into the system checks and balances to ensure that not one section became too powerful. our government is now republicans vs democrats, cleanly divided and the republicans simply vote what the president wants. maybe this is what the majority of the country wants, but what i saw from kavanaugh on tv, i did not see a man of integrity, composure, or wisdom, all characteristics i would hope for in a supreme court justice.  i‚Äôve been told the economy is doing well under this president; i‚Äôm glad something is good because the three words i used above: integrity, composure, and wisdom has not been demonstrated, in my opinion, by this administration and i, along with a whole bunch of people feel unsafe. this kavanaugh may or may not have raped one or more women. no investigation. i have been, in my lifetime, repeatedly inappropriately touched by a priest, assaulted by a classmate, woken up to a different classmate rubbing himself on me, had a teacher thrust his tongue down my throat before i could get away, catcalled, followed countless times to my car, rubbed up against countless times in a bar...and i‚Äôm just an average woman.  all, i know for sure is that i‚Äôm terrified for my children‚Äôs futures, and we need #metoo and #blacklivesmatter movements. we need social change because the current state of affairs is messed up. it‚Äôs not fair to have to explain rape to my 8 year old because he heard it about something with the supreme court. i love the united states. i would really love to be proud of her too. maybe one day soon, the actions of our country will be enough said. ‚ù§Ô∏è

text: well, it's been a difficult week of flashbacks and reflections on my own traumas and what i could have done differently. the message to survivors the moment the senate voted a blatant liar #kavanaugh onto the #supremecourt was that there is no point going through the trauma of reliving painful memories to seek justice because privileged men won't be held accountable even by women in power who should know better. today feels like it did back on nov. 9th 2016 when a serial sexual assaulter was elected president.  but i take solace in that they may have won the battle but we are strengthening and uniting to win the war on those who think they are entitled to our bodies, our money, our jobs, our work, our peace of mind. we are so much stronger.  we will #votethemout #ibelievechristine #ibelieveanita #ibelievesurvivors #metoo #whyididntreport

text: anyone who knows me, knows that one of the causes i am a most passionate advocate for, is empowering women to find and use their voice, stand up for their beliefs and confidently follow their passions. and an organisation that i truly believe has a lasting impact on women (me included) and that i love to talk about is @iamthatgirl ‚ù§Ô∏è today i am so proud of us. #thatgirltakesover was a resounding success, with live events in 12 states across the country. i‚Äôm honoured to have been involved in planning the new york event in partnership with @thecamaraderienyc - a day-long forum bringing women together to empower, spread positivity and inspire them to walk confidently down the path that is theirs. standing in a circle at the end of the day, each sharing or takeaways from the event, i felt a huge sense of community with these women i had just met. community is powerful, y‚Äôall. and as women, especially now, we need to show up for each other, to lift each other up, to find our voices and support each other, more than ever. thank you to the incredible speakers; @rozthediva @nicoleacardoza @kieroyale for your brave open talk on pursuing your passions; @mcquailejenny @supermodelemme for inspiring us to advocate for ourselves and all women to demand diversity in fashion; @delaneycolaio @alexxwhiitaker for moving us with your open discussions of overcoming; @katiehorwitch for so eloquently pushing us to practice positive and kind talk to ourselves and others. thank you iatg and the camaraderie for making this happen, @christyreevesla for working tirelessly for this day and for coming all the way to nyc to be with us and @missalexisjones for founding this organisation which continues to change the lives of so many young women.

text:
things i have been told in my life: don't wear your hair in a ponytail because it's easier to grab, don't walk alone at night, don't wear leggings/short shorts/dresses/show cleavage/etc because it causes temptation, don't listen to music while out running because you need to hear your surroundings, check in your car windows before entering it and lock all the doors as soon as you get inside, always carry a weapon (keys between fingers) when walking alone, don't let anyone know when you are home alone...the list goes on. i say this not to say "men are the problem" but to say "there is real fear - based on real experiences - living in many women in this country right now". 1 of 3 women will be sexually assaulted in their life. i was in 8th grade when that statistic came to life for me. i pray daily the my baby sister will somehow luck (because honestly it is luck with a statistic that high) into being in the other 2 of 3. these conversations are not happening because women want attention. they're happening because women want change. safety. a better world for the generations to come. #wecandobetter .
.
.

when i was 7, my dad's friend took me on a camping trip. it was just me and him and i was so excited. the first night was fine; we stayed in a hotel, he spoiled me and i was having so much fun. the second night, we stayed in a tent together and he raped me. he put a pillow over my head to stop the screams. he beat me and whispered disgusting obscenities in my ear. this contunued throughout the whole night. the next day before we went home, he told me to wear long pants and tops to cover the bruises, otherwise he'd come back and do it again. a few days later, mum saw the bruises and took me to a doctor. the doctor confirmed that i was raped and then who it was. he was then convicted but i don't remember for how long or on what grounds and i can't work up the courage to ask mum about it. he hasn't been spoken about in our house since. #metoo #nomore #metoomovement

text:
this isn't simply a women vs. men conversation. it's really not. but it is about power. and telling the truth. and an ability to listen. it's about stopping the epidemic of readily dismissing someone when they share one of the most traumatic events of their lives and not reflecting on what it means to them. or worse, using that trauma as a bargaining chip. it's about no longer letting it fall on deaf ears to embrace a false sense of power that has become so toxic. the kind of power that constantly thinks it needs to bring others down to build itself up. the kind of power that can't move past a single point of view.

we can so quickly accuse someone of being angry or out to get us or against us instead of seeing the world from their perspective. we can quickly dimiss someone when they tell us how they feel or don't feel because we falsely buy in to the idea that they don't matter as much as we do. we all live under hierarchy and authority in some way and that helps us march forward, but any time we find reasons to diminish another human being so that we can build on our sense of power, we have lost our way. some of us were handed that power and we think everyone has it equally, but that isn't true. and it's time for change.
how can we elevate others instead of diminishing their pain? how can we honor someone when they show us who they are?  how can we, as a collective, recognize that our default response to deep vulnerability is to poke holes in the story? is that really who we want to be as people? is that creating the sense of freedom and trust that we value? or does it just make us shut down all the more, because if her story isn't believed then why should mine be?

we have to stop pretending and tell the truth. i, too, am a victim of sexual abuse and it has shaped my life in ways i don't even realize. there are so many times when i have held back, bitten my tongue, ignored the comments, but i can't do that anymore. it's not real or honest. beyond #metoo i need to know that people speaking their pain matters.
.
.
#believe #listen #women #men #survivors #findyourvoice #holdspace #painmatters #create #heal #resist #believesurvivors #solidarity #blackfridays

text: i am a woman. me too, three times. my sexuality split in two. one side remained the young child in hiding, afraid and in shock. the other part has been molded by what culture tells me is hot. i‚Äôve been sold an archetype void of soul when it comes to what feminine energy really is. my feminine side shattered into pieces early on. i don‚Äôt run from this or stuff it all inside. have always strongly needed to understand and heal my wounded heart. i feel my purpose is to use suffering to transform into my true self, soul living on the outside. therefore i don‚Äôt hate my perpetrators. i don‚Äôt fear them...anymore. i used to but that‚Äôs the great thing about healing. you actually heal. i know it‚Äôs not my job to heal from the assaults i did not cause. i know i‚Äôm innocent. i know it‚Äôs not fair. i‚Äôve accepted all of those stories and the pain that will never be met with logic. i‚Äôve accepted the loss of my sexual innocence. i have surrendered to the experience as meant to be. this does not mean i see assault as good. i don‚Äôt see it in terms of good versus bad. i don‚Äôt demonize those who commit harm. we all commit harm. we‚Äôre all products of systemic abuse. it‚Äôs a spectrum-how we handle the long line of collective abuse our bloodlines have endured. i feel like, who am i to judge how well or not well you‚Äôve handled your systemic abuse? i feel for us all. i know there are men in power who don‚Äôt fall into this category. i can feel the difference between a shattered man who needs to heal and a soulless poser of a man. like those in power right now. it‚Äôs as if they don‚Äôt have souls. i trust this feeling. i know the cruelest of cruel exists. i‚Äôve been prey. i‚Äôve had ptsd, i‚Äôve been suicidal, i‚Äôve healed from the deepest of suffering. today, i love being in my body. i celebrate my body. this feeling is new. i feel the feminine setting free within me. those predators no longer own me. the broken men are no longer tied to my heart. i‚Äôm liberated in my soul. i feel we are all on this path and when enough of us are free inside, the overlords will vanish because the true self holds all the power. we are not commodities. we are free. #liberatethefeminine #metoo #poetryinmotion

text: i am deeply disturbed and in awe but not surprised by the vote to forward judge brett kavanaugh into the highest point of the supreme court. to quote senator kamala harris ‚Äúwe talk about the impact one individual can have. impact on people you‚Äôll never meet and peoples names you‚Äôll never know. whether a person can exercise their constitutional right to cast a ballot if judge kavanaugh sits on that throne. whether a woman with breast cancer can afford health care or is forced off life saving treatment. whether a gay or transgender worker is treated with dignity or may be treated as a second class citizen. or a young woman who got pregnant at 15 is forced is forced to give birth or has to go to back alley to get an abortion. whether a president of the united states is held accountable or whether he will be above the law.‚Äù less than 4 weeks ago the presidents lawyer and campaign chairmen were each found guilty or pleaded guilty to 8 felonies. the presidents personal lawyer under oath said the president directed him to conduct a federal crime, yet that same president was racing to appoint him to a lifetime position to the highest court of our land. whatever side you say you believe in... no matter what.... no man or woman accused of sexual assault should be appointed to that highest standard. it is scientifically proven that sexual assault victims as a defense mechanism in their brain push aside their assault as a way to survive. they forget the where abouts and how they got there , how they got home, but what they do remember is who did it and how it fucking felt. your president this weekend mocked dr. ford and belittled her. and he who holds one of the highest powers, and guides the highest powers , and anointed and encouraged the greats powers (kavanaugh) are the men in this country that cast fear in the #metoo movement and that the women and men wont come forward and that no one will listen. and if they do come forward feel discouraged that their credibility isn‚Äôt sufficient. we live in a day and time where we must speak up for those that can‚Äôt be heard and do something. i‚Äôm sick of this. i‚Äôm disgusted. #metoo #kamalaharris #justice #senate #judiciarycommittee

text: today‚Äôs #witchybooktober prompt is favorite author. instead of choosing one, i chose as many of my favorite female writers that i could fit into this photo! i wanted to make a more aggressive bookish shape to represent the upsetting happenings of this day, which essentially was going to be a finger. however, i am a person that would rather deal with corruption, anger, and frustration by use of love and strength. hence, i decided to make a heart on fire. because, today only enlightened the #metoo movement and women‚Äôs strength! i have definitely seen the patriarchal ways of this world in general and in the workplace. it always makes my blood boil, and i have been let go before for standing up for what is right.  no one should hold precedence over anyone, we should all be treated fairly and equally. it‚Äôs not right to be bullied, mistreated, hated, harmed, or not given equal opportunity. what happened today was disgusting, but we can still fight against the injustice of our world. ‚úäüèª‚úäüèº‚úäüèΩ‚úäüèæ‚úäüèø no question for today, just want to spread some love and empowerment. if you‚Äôd like to share a story, words of encouragement, or just vent go right ahead! #bookphotography #female #riseup #empowerment #strength #strong #women #equality #justiceforall #booklover #reader #love #respect #instamood #ibelievechristineblaseyford #photooftheday #insta #bookclub #bookstagram #reader #reading #bestoftheday @kimmersbooks #photooftheday #heart #life #cool #awesome #instadaily #beauty #mybookfeatures

text:
on a day like today, i am remembering my own strength. remembering the power of my voice. remembering the realities that have come true for me, that my abuelas + tatara-abuelas dreamed of. remembering the fierceness they gifted me with, after years and years of fighting and grit. forever grateful for the legacy they gave me, and that we are building together. i am sure you have that same strength in you, too. so vamos: rise up, wise up, eyes up, porque si se puede, mi gente. pa‚Äôlante üíõ

text:
#metoo : there were so many days i could've smiled but chose not to. i didn't want to be seen or noticed. i didn't want to attract attention. i dimmed and belittled myself. i didn't speak up about what happened to me. and i still don't. i felt weak and ashamed. i felt like it was my fault. my decision to not speak up was that, my decision, and it doesn't invalidate anything that happened to me. because it did happen. but i want to stand in solidarity with those who have either chosen to speak up or not. you deserve to smile and to be loved and love life. we may feel like our experiences don't matter because of today's vote but we matter. be well in your heart and mind. and that will make us all happy. i love you üíõ

pc shout-out to @itshannahduhhhhh for capturing my smile in all its glory. i've never loved my smile more than i did that day. üß°

text:
just another saturday 
i met her 6 months ago when we camped out in front of city hall to fight for homeless women facing assault and sexual assault. she jumped right in and helped us organize. 
she's been through hell and back. she is a survivor.

she organized the #metoo march in hollywood last year.

she organized the march against kavanaugh last thursday. 
she's organizing another #metoo march on november 10th this year.

she has personally walked in a homeless single mom with a baby looking for help from the streets of downtown into a shelter. 
we are proud to call her a #shedoes warrior fighting for our homeless women in la.

today is not a loss. today is not a day that will change history because brenda gutierrez (@animelvr83)will fight today, tomorrow and any other day for survivors.

she is a fighter! she is hope!

be inspired & fight and today will be just another saturday!

text:
i was sexually abused at the age of 8. after 16 years, i told 1 person. up until today, i‚Äôve only told my truth to 3 people, 17 years later. ‚Ä¢
i can‚Äôt tell you the exact dates it happened, or how many times it happened, or even specific details of each encounter. i don‚Äôt know how it eventually stopped, and i can‚Äôt even tell you how i coped with it. ‚Ä¢
what i do know, is the emotional scarring and internal pain one feels are long-lasting and traumatizing to the body, spirit and mind. i can tell you first-hand of the guilt and shame so many have carried with them their entire lives, all because of something they didn‚Äôt ask for.
‚Ä¢
i look back at so much of my life and realize how many of my doubts, insecurities, fears, and broken relationships all have been inter-woven and stemmed from the violation of my body. coming to terms with who i was as a man, sexually, i knew i would be forced to deal with my past. at times, i‚Äôve wished no one would have found out, because i was afraid and knew it would be used against me. a ‚Äúbargaining chip‚Äù or proof, that me being gay was perverted, shameful, or caused by something. as much as you can try to shelve the pain or thoughts, they linger. accepting yourself is already a complex pill to swallow, but having to complicate that with trauma is something that one should never have to go through.
‚Ä¢
it sounds bizarre, but i no longer feel any anger towards the person or situation at this point in my life. i‚Äôve learned that in order for me to survive, i have to love myself and embrace everything i am in order to be liberated. it may seem insignificant, but i‚Äôve realized every ‚Äúboundary-pushing‚Äù thing i have done has been a way for myself to regain control and own who i am without remorse, freely. something i feel that was taken away from me.
‚Ä¢
i don‚Äôt say this for sympathy or sorrow, but rather for the intent to encourage. for all of the women and men & those who have endured and fought, and are still fighting. thank you. i also say it for myself. i‚Äôve chosen to not be bound or ashamed any longer by things that i cannot change. i‚Äôm free. #metoo

text:
writing my way through some thoughts + feelings on american womanhood this afternoon. dedicated to all of you, fellow females //‚óºÔ∏èthis weekend, @ the 1-year mark since sexual assault allegations against harvey weinstein inspired #metoo, the senate judiciary committee confirmed supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh. it‚Äôs done. he‚Äôs in. 
on friday, committee chairman chuck grassley spoke on behalf of the judge, meandering around an implication that on-paper accomplishments of men like kavanaugh render them incapable of sexual assault. clearly the weinstein / #metoo connection was lost on grassley. 
he went on to mutter, ‚Äúin a previous era, this highly qualified nominee would have received unanimous support in the senate.‚Äù you nailed it, chuck: in a previous era, kavanaugh may well have been confirmed unanimously. 
but in this era, more & more women offer their stories, invest in their own truths, blow apart & rebuild oppressive systems, move goddamn mountains of sexism, & do it with patience, balance, & humility. we‚Äôre complicating male-dominated narratives w/ our voices exactly how we need to & it‚Äôs hitting the grassleys & kavanaughs & weinsteins of the world exactly where it should. 
the badass women who shared & defended the value & validity of their stories during this confirmation process weren‚Äôt out pushing a conspiracy, mistaken memory, or misrepresentation. 
it was always about truth. & for some, that‚Äôs the most inconvenient thing to face‚Äîparticularly when it threatens patriarchal power & status. 
the backwards misogyny & inequity (on so many levels) of every american era thus far is shitty, but it‚Äôs shifting. whether others accept truth from womankind or not, roads of justice & voting power & community are still here for us to march down together. the #believewomen banner still needs waving. there are more places for us to go. a woman-led washington is on the horizon.  we‚Äôve gotta keep running‚Äîliterally & figuratively.

text:
"panty portrait: bush" from the panty project, 2 of 51
.

fiber art, archival pigment print on museum cotton rag, 
19 x 14 inches
.
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
following this long week in review of the u.s. supreme court nominee hearings, i became both deeply saddened...and encouraged. womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
everyone is saying, ‚Äúunbelievable!‚Äù. but it is completely believable. more than 20 years after anita hill‚Äôs testimony we have not moved an inch, it seems, in many ways. another man in a position of power who thinks of women as the other - only present when in relation to the man - the self. the self is able to be without identification or apology of identity, the other is allowed to be only as a reflection of the self. ‚Äúrepresentation of the world, like the world itself, is the work of men; they describe it from their own point of view, which they confuse with absolute truth. when an individual (or a group of individuals) is kept in a situation of inferiority, the fact is that he is inferior. but the significance of the verb to be must be rightly understood here; it is in bad faith to give it a static value when it really has the dynamic hegelian sense of "to have become." yes, women on the whole are today inferior to men; that is, their situation affords them fewer possibilities. the question is: should that state of affairs continue? 
many men hope that it will continue; not all have given up the battle.‚Äù it‚Äôs not going to be sudden, but there will be change. no more words. the only way out is through. #brettkavanaugh #ibelieveher #anitahill #christineblaseyford #metoo #stopkavanaugh #supremecourt #abortion #simonedebeauvoir

text: there is beauty on a lone road. i finally feel like i‚Äôm in control of something. it‚Äôs quiet, but i try not to think and pull my heart into pining. the tightest thing i‚Äôve felt lately has been this seat belt across my chest. you don‚Äôt even text anymore. it‚Äôs like you never existed at all if i turn my head in the right direction... some days are for running away from your problems, and then realizing they might not be problems. some moments are for remembering that emotion isn‚Äôt an ugly word, and that your rejection of mine says nothing about me. some love is meant to be shared, and some is meant to be felt alone on an empty road en route to nothing and no one. it‚Äôs just a passing thought to be triggered out of silence. if dreams are just filtered memories, then let my heart be openly mocked and consumed in crowded rooms rather than ignored altogether, for none of it is anything but traffic going in the opposite direction. hello. goodbye. i‚Äôm not too cool to say i loved you, or to say it still hurts sometimes. it wouldn‚Äôt mean much to me if i could control it like my car on this road. stopping for gas now, but i‚Äôll probably find myself circling the same idea in fifteen minutes.

text:
this is my daughter. my first baby. today the election of brett kavanaugh reminded me that despite being born in 2005 and a teen now that her generation, my generation and generations to come will have to continue to fight. fight for equity and equality. fight to be heard. will have to ask themselves what they need to do to protect themselves. she will fight because she is the daughter of a fighter, the granddaughter of a fighter, the niece of a fighter. it's in her blood and she will shatter ceilings everywhere. but her road is not easy. her road is scattered with old white men who want to control her body, her mind, her career, her paycheck, men who want to have a say over her uterus, of what she learns and how she dreams. but she will get up as she has continued to get up, despite her own hardships. she will dream and she will achieve and we will celebrate her. 
#metoo #motherhood #daughter #love #raisingdaughters #glassceiling #dream #istandwithdrford #fucktrump #prochoice

i've been on a real high today from all the glass, friends & love ... i then hurt my soul a little by catching up on the news.  with my heart feeling heavy, this is the card i drew. üå≥

in many ways i hate where this country is headed.  i have to stop and remind myself of the tiny sliver of good happening too.  i am proud of all the people out there being strengthened by the #metoo movement.  i'm proud of a new awareness being pushed into the light.  i am proud of this huge force of people banding together to stand up against inappropriate behavior, once and for all.  may my niece and nephew grow up in a new world where they will never, ever have to say 'me too'. üí•

text:
i am angry. 
i am angry and heartbroken. 
i angry and heartbroken and unsurprised. 
we live is a culture that does not listen to or believe women, especially women of color and trans women. 
we live in a culture that values protecting toxic masculinity over protecting women. 
as kavanuagh was confirmed today, millions of women were shown, again, that this world does not care about us. 
the white, male politicians keep talking about how we need to ‚Äúband together and find our similarities‚Äù and while i understand the intention behind this, i disagree with what they are saying. 
i think that we need to let oppressed people be angry at their oppression because being angry gives us our autonomy back. 
telling us to stop being angry further dehumanizes us. 
we are allowed to be angry. 
we are allowed to be angry at the systems and the people who oppress us as well as those who are complicit. 
saying that we should try to ‚Äúput ourselves in their shoes‚Äù (meaning putting ourselves in our predators shoes) puts all the blame and responsibility on to the oppressed. 
this is not our job. 
it is not our job rip ourselves open and prove our suffering. 
it is not our job to make you care about the violence we face. 
if you have privilege: amplify marginalized voices. 
white people: it is your job to fight against racism. 
straight & cis people: it is your job to fight against homophobia & transphobia. 
men: it is your job to fight against misogyny & the patriarchy. 
step up. do the fucking work or get out of the way. the revolution is here.

text:
#swipe #‚úä despite the credible accusations of sexual assault against brett kavanaugh by dr. christine ford, on friday, he garnered enough votes on the senate floor to win a lifetime appointment to the supreme court today. watching dr. ford testify about her experience was excruciatingly painful, especially compared to kavanaugh‚Äôs ranting and weeping over his love of beer. in addition to being an accused sexual assailant, kavanaugh also has extremely conservative (and ill-informed) views on abortion and other civil rights issues. it‚Äôs a dark day, and it‚Äôs deeply sad that dr. ford had her life picked apart to defend us and kavanaugh is still getting what he wants. 
truth is truth: we recognize it, if we are at all human.  i believe what @ladygaga says in this interview.  i believe @ladygaga because i am a sexual assault survivor, and what she has to say rings true. the damage is enormous--it is psychological, and physical.  any man who makes light of this is no man at all.  the suffering is genuine and never really goes away.  it makes any kind of functional nomality impossible in some cases--i know--and changes lives in ways that no one should have to deal with. women need to vote, and make that vote felt to a degree no one has ever seen before.  women do epic things every day without recognition, but now is the time to claim that recognition.  now is the time to work with allies who understan--and change the rape culture forever. we cannot let these brutes triumph.  we must do whatever we have to do to shut down the "boys will be boys" shit and call it out for the criminality that it is.  we must educate, and overcome the willing ignorance that promotes inequality and privilege.

it is time for revolution: it is time for humanity to show the best that it can be.
.

today confirms what the world already tells us every day still holds true: that survivors experiences with sexual assault don‚Äôt matter; that this, today, right now, is why sexual assault is so underreported; that even the most under qualified man in the world still beat out a woman and is our president; that now, kavanaugh is sworn in as supreme court justice, for life.
‚Ä¢
it‚Äôs okay to feel a lot of things.
- rage
- anger
- frustration
- sadness
- disappointment
‚Ä¢
you‚Äôre allowed to feel it all.
‚Ä¢
i also want you to remember that you matter, that i believe you, and that today, although so fucking discouraging, does not have to foreshadow the future.
‚Ä¢
sexual assault is not a partisan issue.
vote. vote. vote. vote.
‚Ä¢

text:
i have nothing to add when @lilasugerman says it all:  every 98 seconds, an american is sexually assaulted.  90% of those sexual assaults are performed on women and as of 1998, an estimated 17.7 million american women have been victims of attempted or completed rape.
1 in 5 women will be raped at some point in their lives. even though the crime of rape and sexual assault is absolutely and utterly atrocious, rape remains as one of the most unreported crimes. 63% of sexual assaults are not reported. and of sexual assaults that are reported 1-2% will be false. this is why we need to believe survivors, this is why i choose to believe dr. ford. by confirming kavanaugh the senate has sent a very clear message that these women‚Äôs voices aren‚Äôt heard when they should be. these women deserve to be heard. this isn‚Äôt about being part of a political party or being liberal. this is about being a teenage girl living in fear, fear that this sends a message that a white male in power can get away with nearly anything. #metoo #whatshesaid #believesurvivors #hopeforthefuture

text:
i have struggled to find the right words over this past week. to be frank, dr christine blasey ford‚Äôs testimony caused some serious demons of mine to rise back up to the surface. i am finally ready to share these words after today‚Äôs senate vote. 
i believe her, but it‚Äôs not about believing. it‚Äôs about caring. it‚Äôs about giving every single one of these cases their deserved attention and caring about the victims. i do not see why any person would bring this upon themselves if it weren‚Äôt true, but that‚Äôs besides the point. these men in positions of power need to be held to the highest of standards, and i commend dr ford for attempting to do just that. unfortunately, once again, the united states government has decided that a woman is not enough. 
i did not report my assault. in fact, i have only told one person about it. for months afterwards, my body was not my own. i couldn‚Äôt decide if i had experienced assault or a ‚Äúweird incident‚Äù, as i honestly could not remember many of the details (my subconscious must have chosen to forget.) i was not raped and therefore did not feel like i had a right to point the finger at my assailant. i was too worried about what people would think of me, what it would do to his life and mine. to this day, i see the man who assaulted me from time to time. he was drunk, and for the longest time i believed that excuse in order to push it as far from my mind as i could. but just because i did not report it, does not mean it didn‚Äôt happen. as much as i wish it hadn‚Äôt. 
check on your friends today. check on those that you know are survivors and check on those that you don‚Äôt. love each other. we are fighting a hard battle and we must press on. ‚ù§Ô∏èüí™üèºüò¢

i believe her, but it‚Äôs not about believing. it‚Äôs about caring. it‚Äôs about giving every single one of these cases their deserved attention and caring about the victims. i do not see why any person would bring this upon themselves if it weren‚Äôt true, but that‚Äôs besides the point. these men in positions of power need to be held to the highest of standards, and i commend dr ford for attempting to do just that. unfounately, once again, the united states government has decided that a woman is not enough. 
i did not repo my assault. in fact, i have only told one person about it. for months afterwards, my body was not my own. i couldn‚Äôt decide if i had experienced assault or a ‚Äúweird incident‚Äù, as i honestly could not remember many of the details (my subconscious must have chosen to forget.) i was not raped and therefore did not feel like i had a right to point the finger at my assailant. i was too worried about what people would think of me, what it would do to his life and mine. to this day, i see the man who assaulted me from time to time. he was drunk, and for the longest time i believed that excuse in order to push it as far from my mind as i could. but just because i did not repo it, does not mean it didn‚Äôt happen. as much as i wish it hadn‚Äôt. 
check on your friends today. check on those that you know are survivors and check on those that you don‚Äôt. love each other. we are fighting a hard battle and we must press on. ‚ù§Ô∏èüí™üèºüò¢

today, i engaged in my first act of civil disobedience with @womensmarch. i stood with and defended survivors, women, african americans, latinxs, asians, lqbtqias, immigrants, allies, and anyone else who believes in equality and human rights. i learned about direct action from women that have been fighting this fight for years. and let me tell you, that shit was invigorating. it was what life is all about. sitting on the capitol steps, watching the police swarm, i didn‚Äôt feel afraid. i looked out at the crowd on the other side of the fence supporting us, and i felt overwhelmed with emotion. i felt hurt, angry, sad, disgusted, betrayed, trapped, invisible, and exhausted. but more than anything, i felt activated. i felt the movement rising up. i felt a part of something bigger than myself. i felt electric, and i realized that something magical is happening right fucking now. we, the people, are the powerful ones. and we, together, can change things. our stories matter. we won‚Äôt ever forget what happened during this entire sham of a scotus confirmation, but we will overcome it and we will vote. them. out. ‚úäüèº

.

.

text:
this is a vulnerable post but i want my voice to be heard and i want everyone to know where i stand.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
there are many women who do not speak about their sexual assault and for many reasons. it does not mean it didn‚Äôt happen. i am one of those women. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i was raped at 15 by a man who was in his late 20‚Äôs (26 or 27 at least). i was intoxicated but i remember.  the memory is still there 10 years later. i didn‚Äôt tell anyone because i was scared and ashamed. for awhile, i made it up in my head that maybe i was asking for it along with all kinds of other reasons. i‚Äôve dealt with it some here and there but with time it just got further and further away. it was rape. it was horrible. and no reason that i could come up with in my head can justify that.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
as women we need to fight. as men, you need to fight with us and not throw us into a corner because we waited years to come out and say something. what is really sad is that there are so many men that have been sexually abused also but don't share about it and somehow some of those men are standing against us. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
let your voice be heard. register to vote. stand for what is right and best for this country. #metoo #novemberiscoming #believesurvivors #believewomen #vote #yesallwomen #womensreality #timesup #tothegirls #whyistand

text:
‚Äúthough the sex to which i belong is considered weak you will nevertheless find me a rock that bends to no wind‚Äù -queen elizabeth i 
one of my all time fav quotes. not because she was a queen or a princess and had a lot of money but because she was a strong and powerful woman when women had no voice. and she refused to back down to any man because of her gender. to this date she is still considered one of the best rulers of all time and she radically progressed not only women but the times in general. i am not a man hating feminist but i am a feminist. i went to an all girls catholic high school, i was raised by a strong woman and both my grandmothers are/were women that demanded respect. i say this because while i am utterly sick of hearing about the kavanaugh/trump/ford saga, i am so happy that it is bringing to light something that for so long many of us have simply smiled and ignored. women are repeatedly victimized by men. and it‚Äôs not ok. and i‚Äôm  glad that men now feel fear because maybe that will prevent some of them from saying or doing something that they shouldn‚Äôt. (i‚Äôm not talking false accusations here). i have always been a people pleaser and have often allowed things that bothered me or made me uncomfortable because i didn‚Äôt want to be a ‚Äúb$tch‚Äù or to ‚Äúrock the boat.‚Äù i wanted to be liked. and this is almost hypocritical because i consider myself a strong female yet i too allowed things that i shouldn‚Äôt have and have not spoken up when i should have. but now that changes. and i don‚Äôt care if this offends males because it‚Äôs your own narcissism that flips the script making yourselves a victim. (not pointing fingers because we are all guilty of doing that at times.) but be aware of it. listen instead of getting emotional. treat women with the dignity and respect that we deserve. my gender is finding our voice and we‚Äôre not going to be quiet anymore! 
p.s another unpopular opinion: i hated 50 shades of grey simply because i couldn‚Äôt respect a girl that wants to be dominated by a man. ugh lol #girlpower
.
.
#genderequality #women #feminism #wewantaseatatthetable #united #strongwomen #westandtogether #silentnomore #metoo #girls #whoruntheworld

text: was it my fault? i thought that for many years the abuse that happened to me was my fault, that i brought it upon myself somehow. i spent years trying to please those who hurt me, feeling that i needed their acceptance and love in order to feel whole. if i knew then what i do now.... if i could go back and tell myself that the #abuse i went through in my childhood had nothing to do with me, i would. through years of clawing my way through conflicted emotions, i finally discovered that i was not a #victim but that i was a #strongwoman that deserved better in my life but also in my #warriormentality. i took my life back and now work with other #abusesurvivors to see what they endured did not break them, and that they do have a #voice to #transform and #overcome and have all their #dreams come true. it‚Äôs my passion to #enpowerwomen #empowersurvivors to live #abundant lives. will you be my next #successstory ? #metoo #ibelieveinsurvivors #whyididntreport #spiritualcleansing #survivingabuse #bossmentality #abusewarrior #abusecoach #abuseninja #mentalclarity #focusonyourself #fightback #speakup #letyourvoicebeheard #takebackyourvoice #hearme #lifecoach

text:
what a day on capitol hill. walking through the crowd of protestors, shouts of degradation were showered upon me. from the repeated ‚Äúf**k you‚Äùs to ‚Äúshame, shame, shame‚Äù to ‚Äúwhite women are misogynists too!‚Äù to the most horrifying of all: ‚Äúi hope brett kavanaugh rapes you.‚Äù being a conservative woman in this crowd today was difficult, to say the least. but i am proud to be both an advocate for victims of sexual assault and also a citizen bold enough to exercise her first amendment rights, standing in solidarity with those who defend the (unpopular) tenets of the american political tradition and believe our nation rests firmly on a foundation of justice, made possible by due process and rule of law. the #metoo movement deserves better than the political weaponization of sexual assault. 
we have lost civility and become barbarians.

i was proud today to support the outstanding #justicekavanaugh in the midst of such hostility. (note the photo with cluster of people with their middle fingers high in the sky - this was taken as our vice president walked down the steps of the senate.) pray for our nation, friends. we need all the help we can get.

#istandwithbrett #confirmkavanaugh #confirmation

text:
‚Äúcompanies whose leaders are at least 30% female have net margins 6 percent higher than companies with no women among the senior ranks. venture capitalists pride themselves on being data-driven, but this data apparently didn‚Äôt convince. what did?‚Äù the #metoo movement! 
women speaking out was the tipping point and now women are highly sought after for leadership positions. it‚Äôs time for women to use their voices!

are you using your voice? 
i am! 
finally! 
but this was a long journey, i was embarrassed to be seen, i would shame myself for saying what‚Äôs on my mind even if it was valuable to others, and i was terrified to be in front of people especially on stage!

that all changed four years ago when @dianeallenspeaker, who speaks on how to own your a-game, helped me transform my career and empowered me to use my voice! 
i wouldn‚Äôt even sit at the front of a room, i wouldn‚Äôt make videos, i struggled to feel confident is delivering my message no matter the platform. but i had a big vision for myself.

this vision would require me to be seen, to use my voice, be in video and to get on stage! üò¨üò¨üò¨ after working with diane it all changed. i speak in front of lots of people. i can get on stage and deliver a message with five seconds notice, i own that stage! people tell me i have a powerful stage presence and i‚Äôm a great teacher. i wouldn‚Äôt of believed this about myself ten years ago. 
now i own my a-game, speak with confidence and looooove being on stage! (literally i‚Äôm addicted to it) 
tomorrow we are doing a facebook live and you get to join us and learn how to speak without clamming up, how to discover the source of your confidence and the source of your voice, and how to communicate in the most compelling and convincing way.

diane, along with my determination, hard work, and commitment to empowering people to love their lives and breakthrough their money blocks, got me to a place where i am owning my a-game, getting my message out there and feeling confident and in my power from stage!

watch our fb live, this woman is incredible!!!!

text: surrender to passion. right now what‚Äôs going on in the political arena,  it‚Äôs still amazing that the voices of so many are being silenced again. i have many friends speaking up and marching and showing presence to demand a better political representation. i cheer my warrior women on right now and the men who support them. it takes a lot of courage and energy. it‚Äôs easy to get burned out when your voice repeatedly gets ignored and silenced. find your own voice and have the courage to speak your truth and let no one disregard you. it‚Äôs time for us all to speak up and have healthy discussions openly. we all have anger within us through repression and abuse, we need to move that energy in healthy ways, so we stop repeating the cycle of pain in our life. there is much more to say to that, but i am feeling exhausted currently through seeing it still hasn‚Äôt changed a bit in the political arena. power over people seems to be the political strategy again...as we have learned nothing. together we are stronger, divided we are weaker. we all have voices, but why is it so hard to find a good balance of peace within us, do we all still have so much shadow that we rather play out than face our own pain and deal with it in healthy ways instead of avoiding and projecting? #sunreitarot #tarot #tarotreading #politics #currentstateofaffairs #justice #peace #wethepeople #ourvoice #ourvoices #feminerising #metoo #weareallone #shadowside #truth #truthisinyourheart #wecount #wecandobetter #kavanaugh #kavanaughhearings #justicesystemfail #justicesystemreform

text:
gladiolus üå∏ strength || this wasn‚Äôt the next flower on the list, and i even skipped a few days of #inktober ‚Äîbut it was important for me to do this today. as women, we‚Äôre raised to believe that we don‚Äôt have power over our bodies‚Äî how they‚Äôre used (by ourselves, by our partners) or how they‚Äôre perceived. we‚Äôre taught that our bodies are objects. we learn that our safety is not a guarantee. we change our routines. we look over our shoulders. we pick shoes to wear out based on how easy they might be to run in. we apologize for being abused, we apologize for everything. when poison tries to reassert itself in our lives we feel guilty or cornered or trapped. this isn‚Äôt my best work or even my best observation of anatomy. but this is a reminder to myself that no one controls my body but me. i will not be intimidated or bullied. i refuse. gladiolus are for strength. i think all women are gladiators. never forget your strength and never let anyone take it from you, either. .
#feminist #girlpower #metoo #empoweringwomen #art #sketch #inkdrawing #prismacolor #copicmarkers #lineart

text:
judge brett kavanaugh, president trump's second nominee to the supreme court, was confirmed to the court on saturday with a senate vote largely divided along party lines, 50-48.
.
the committee paused the nomination process for a week so the fbi could investigate sexual misconduct allegations. afterwards, republicans declared that the fbi had not found any corroborating witnesses, while democrats complained the fbi didn't look hard or long enough.
.
mr. trump tweeted shortly after kavanaugh was confirmed that the new member of the supreme court would be sworn in saturday evening.
.
"i applaud and congratulate the u.s. senate for confirming our great nominee, judge brett kavanaugh, to the united states supreme court. later today, i will sign his commission of appointment, and he will be officially sworn in. very exciting!" mr. trump wrote.
.
(source: time, cbs news)

text:
i have a love-hate with october. fall is hands down my favorite. i‚Äôm beyond obsessed with everything pumpkin flavored, all the leaves change, and ski season is just around the corner. this october is my 7 year anniversary of being raped by someone whom i loved and trusted. it‚Äôs been a journey of suppressed memories, numbness, tightness, confusion, nightmares, triggers, and more pain than i would ever wish on anyone. it‚Äôs also been a journey of peace, forgiveness, acceptance, quiet moments, strength, release, and an overwhelming amount of love and compassion. there‚Äôs been so much i‚Äôve learned, and so many ways i‚Äôve grown. 1 in 4 women and 1 in 6 men are survivors of sexual assault. a huge part of discrediting shame is bringing it to the light, and sharing your story. this is mine: i am a survivor, but i am not defined by it. i am weak, and i am strong, often times within the same moment. i am worthy of love. god did not plan for this to happen to me, he allowed agency, and he has wept by my side every time tears have fallen. but most importantly, i am enough exactly as i am. 
#metoo #mentalhealthawareness #survivor #october #rapesurvivor #therapy #somuchtherapy #likesooomuchtherapy #lds #happiness #healing #sharemystory #prayerworksmiracles #imperfectlyperfect #iamenough #youareenough  #brenebrown #love #havecompassionforyourself #choosehappiness #choosejoy #chooselove #chooseforgiveness #chooselife #loveyourself #innerpeace
name: Hallie Platt

text: while many wounds have been reopened this past month with dr. ford‚Äôs testimony-i am sure that her courage has inspired tons of survivors to come forward and share and relive their trauma to also help others. these past two years have confirmed a lot of bad realizations i‚Äôve kept bottled up since i was able to see wrongdoings happening to my family and those close to me. evil doesn‚Äôt always win, but it can with the help of complacency. it doesn‚Äôt have to though. it is not a ‚Äúfun‚Äù or ‚Äútrendy‚Äù thing to come forward and put trauma into words. call out people who shame others for expressing their emotions. call out problematic people-even if they themselves are disenfranchised and ignorant by choice. call out bigotry-even if it is within your bloodline. and please just fucking vote. stop voting for people who spread propaganda to scare people and confuse them into voting for them and stop not voting due to lack of motivation by a candidate. it‚Äôs not cute or brave. it‚Äôs actually ignorant and a slap in the face to those who are actually affected when evil legislation is passed. vote and believe survivors. vote. democrats protect survivors. #metoo #prouddemocrat #democrat #believesurvivors #love #live #doyou #bestrong #ibelievesurvivors #imwithher #stillwithher #makethemeatit #makeyourabuserexpire #shameabusers #vote #vote #vote üîµüîµüîµ

text: she‚Äôs sleeping peaceful dreams & here i am. my insta has been decidedly about my kids because the ugliness of politics is just a little too much for me. i never share anything political because i don‚Äôt find it helpful. i also have never wanted my statements to project a political stance as a business owner because we truly do welcome everyone. i understand that we all think differently, that‚Äôs a good thing. i do believe that reminding each other of our shared humanity is a good thing. and i don‚Äôt think that it is a good thing that i‚Äôve been scared by a bullying culture of what stating my opinions might open up. i am so inspired and amazed at the courage of so many women to share their experience. courage that i‚Äôve never had. i just need to say it is so real you guys. it is so pervasive. so many of us, more women than anyone would like to believe, have struggled with how, when, or if ever to talk about this type of assault. i also recognize that even though i‚Äôve experienced some things, i‚Äôve still been in a position of privilege & our people of color brothers & sisters have been living the life of ignored injustices every day. i wish i could say that i have been inspired to get politically active to change things. i haven‚Äôt. i am still in the space of simply wanting to hide from it all. i can‚Äôt be the mother & business owner i need to be if i‚Äôm in the throes all the time. that being said, thank you to those of you who use these times as fuel to change the world and broader political spectrum. i can only muster the micro focused work of building a business and family that i pray is empowering to many. love to you all, especially those triggered by all of this in whatever way. i hope we can all find space to process and support each other no matter where we fall on the political spectrum. i pray that we will get past this and paloma & rafael will grow up not being slammed in the face by injustice. if not, i pray that they are both empowered to speak their truth & live with respect for others.  and maybe they‚Äôll have more courage than i do to make a difference.

i could say that i have been inspired to get politically active to change things. i haven‚Äôt. i am still in the space of simply wanting to hide from it all. i can‚Äôt be the mother & business owner i need to be if i‚Äôm in the throes all the time. that being said, thank you to those of you who use these times as fuel to change the world and broader political spectrum. i can only muster the micro focused work of building a business and family that i pray is empowering to many. love to you all, especially those triggered by all of this in whatever way. i hope we can all find space to process and suppo each other no matter where we fall on the political spectrum. i pray that we will get past this and paloma & rafael will grow up not being slammed in the face by injustice. if not, i pray that they are both empowered to speak their truth & live with respect for others.  and maybe they‚Äôll have more courage than i do to make a difference.

text:
i am sad and disgusted. all morning, i entertained a small, faint fantasy in my mind about a kind of topsy turvy october surprise in which a cabal of reasonable, rational republican senators voted against the confirmation of judge brett kavanaugh for the supreme court. instead, reality happened, and everyone performed to expectations. please keep talking, no matter what your opinions are about this confirmation, to your friends and family. keep talking about the obvious manipulation of the hearings and investigations and about the nuances in key figures‚Äô speech and the media coverage, about the anger on both sides, about the very existence of two sides. keep talking about the memories from your lives that dr. christine blasey ford‚Äôs testimony brings to the surface and about the possible futures we can envision and create from where we are, here and now. speak truth to power by telling your stories to people you trust so that we can create change among individuals relating to one another with empathy and so that we can inspire each other to replace fear with love. please vote on november 6. 
#metoo #dismantlepatriarchy

text:
please read

she is not - sarah harvey

she is not here to make you smile.

she does not exist for the sole purpose of making your life easier or making your pain feel less painful.

she does not wake each day to make you gasp or groan with pleasure.

and she sure as hell is not destined to hold your broken pieces politely together.

she is here to inhale her pain and exhale

fire.

she is not a pretty plaything

or a sweet little pet

she is a living, breathing, booming woman

with curiosity flowing through her veins like hot pink lightning,

with thorns on her skin

and colliding particles of electric, mystical mystery in her eyes.

she might look cute, she might look delicate and sweet

but she‚Äôs got a fierce beast inside her

her wild heart.

but that‚Äôs no secret.

because she knows what she‚Äôs not‚Äî- and she is not here to people please until she dies.

she is not here to say pretty, glittery things that make people happy, but have no truth, no meaty substance.

she is not here to hold the crushing weight of the world on her shoulders.

she is not here to hide the flames of her anger behind sweet, sugary, fake little smiles.

she is not the one who will save you.

she knows that she can‚Äôt save anyone, for she nearly lost herself while trying to mend the rips of a thousand broken hearts.

now, she knows‚Äî

she is here to love herself, first.

she is here to inhale pain

and exhale

fire.

she is not a pretty plaything

or a sweet little pet.

she is a living, breathing, booming woman

sent here with a mission, a purpose, a spark

that blooms inside her

when she stops trying to be perfect

when she stops trying to say all the right things

when she stops trying to please everyone else‚Äî

when she stops, lets out a delicious roarin‚Äô scream and asks herself aloud

what do i need?

a bright purple lily blooms in her chest,

it unfurls with decadence and sparkles proudly in the sun, it covers¬†her skin with a silky coat of electric goosebumps.

and in that moment, all is revealed‚Äîa scroll of tattered truths that make her heart beat a little faster‚Äî

she is here to dive deep and she knows it. (continued in comments)

text:
not that it‚Äôs ever easy, but today is an especially hard day to be a victim of sexual assault/abuse. it‚Äôs hard not to be discouraged. i have never spoken about my experience publicly, but i do feel it is important to speak up when it matters. more and more recently i have been experiencing flashbacks and remembering moments i didn‚Äôt want to ever think about again, some i didn‚Äôt know were even there. i‚Äôve been followed in cars, i‚Äôve been yelled at, i‚Äôve been harassed by (old white men) while doing my job, i‚Äôve been through it all. it‚Äôs been a frightening experience, sometimes lonely, always difficult. i‚Äôve been so lucky to have women in my life who haven‚Äôt been judgemental, who have been understanding, and who never tired of listening to me cry and vent. i‚Äôve posted a picture from around the age i was when i was assaulted(maybe older, maybe younger, things are still all messed up in my head) and two of me genuinely happy, years later.

you‚Äôre not alone. my heart and ears are always open. #metoo #fuckkavanaugh.

text:
last night i got to shoot the tn coalition to end domestic and sexual violence‚Äôs pearls and pinstripes gala in celebration of the organization‚Äôs 35th year. and i wept. i stood on the side of the stage after executive director kathy walsh accepted an award and cursed at myself for ruining my mascara as i pulled myself back together. 
i am afraid. constantly. i‚Äôm afraid of walking to my car after work alone. i‚Äôm afraid of sitting in a parking garage for too long or working in a coffee shop alone. i‚Äôm afraid of laughing and chatting with older men but i‚Äôm even more afraid of telling them, ‚Äúno.‚Äù i‚Äôm afraid of telling my own sexual assault story because what i was wearing matters more than his disrespect; my inability to recall the exact time he scratched my face matters more than the physical assault itself. i can go on, but in a society where sexual assault survivors are mere punchlines in trump‚Äôs joke of america, why would i want to? i‚Äôm afraid. 
but last night at the gala, i wasn‚Äôt afraid. i knew that my story was affirmed and understood by everyone in that room. i know they are working to make this community a safer place, to give a voice to those that have lost theirs, and i am more than honored and humbled to have been there. the tn coalition is full of the most dedicated social justice warriors i have ever met and i can only hope to work with them again in the future. i believe in them and i believe wholeheartedly that goodness, kindness, and love will win in the end. let‚Äôs stand together, my loves. believe each other. believe women. love long and hard and often. onward.

text:
protecting ourselves and our children should not be an insurmountable obstacle, but it sure does feel like one sometimes. i don‚Äôt care what donald trump says, finally deciding to stand up for yourself is an act of courage, especially when it entails overcoming paralyzing fear, in order to walk in the light of truth. because it feels easier to just avoid the pain, but your conscience won‚Äôt let you. it is exhausting to subject yourself to that type of discomfort in order to do the right thing. it requires strength of character and stamina. not only do these feats go unrewarded...there are consequences when the manner in which you tell the truth isn‚Äôt believable enough. abusers lie. and the wrong person gets punished. not believing a survivor is as good as punishing them. too often the severity of the trauma we endured is trivialized, and survivors are judged and/or blamed for things that were/are out of our control. trust me, the process of being abused (or overcoming abuse) does not lack humiliation. the bravery of women like dr. ford, who‚Äôve refused to be silenced in the face of opposition, has changed my life and empowered me to acknowledge my own strength, love myself, value the truth even when no one else does, and conquer some of my greatest fears.
...
you can only know what it‚Äôs really like if you‚Äôve lived it. please, try to have an attitude that encourages the creation of survivors, not victims. thank you!
...
october is #domesticviolenceawarenessmonth and i will be posting awareness related content in my feed. this topic is close to my heart, and i thank you in advance for your sensitivity regarding this subject. from my own experience, i‚Äôve found that there is an abundance of misunderstanding regarding the nature of domestic violence, and most people are not equipped to identify the signs of abuse. domestic violence does not stop at physical violence and blatant acts of abuse. let‚Äôs do better to understand this issue because there is more at stake than you could ever imagine.

text_retweet:
our medicine grows deep, strong, and wise the more we are able to integrate difficult experiences over our lives.
due to the latest disturbing us events, i am reposting this #metoo article i wrote over the summer. it is a health issue, actually, when so many of us are needing to metabolize our rage - when our accounts of abuse are not being taken seriously. 
it is relevant to ask, what held back so many women from speaking out publicly for so long? while there are common threads that keep women silent, many of the unspoken forces affect women disproportionately across cultural differences. 
there are major disparities between what it means for me to speak out and what it means for women in more vulnerable populations. women of color face the threat of personally, institutionally, and economically racist responses that generate a whole additional set of concerns. 
and, as bell hooks so aptly asks us, "how do we hold people accountable for wrongdoing and yet at the same time remain in touch with their humanity enough to believe in their capacity to be transformed?"

text:
ok y‚Äôall, here we go. today was #amberroseslutwalk . sadly, i didn‚Äôt get to go, because i had things to do. however, i have a spiel to give about it, especially when taking into consideration the #kavanaugh situation.
let me start by saying that anyone who falsely accuses someone of sexual assault is disgusting and only adding fuel to the fire, which further discredits and silences real victims. however, statistically, a man is more likely to be sexually assaulted by another man than he is to be falsely accused. ‚Äúbut nikki,‚Äù you say, ‚Äúhow are we supposed to handle this overwhelming amount of new accusations from the past?‚Äù well, my friends, you should handle it the same way woman have handled actually being assaulted for thousands of years; with strength and grace.
i‚Äôm not going to go into the science behind generational trauma, or even speak for #yesallwomen . what i will say is this, trauma sucks. being assaulted, feeling like you have nobody to turn to, feeling guilty it even happened, and then carrying the weight of that trauma and blame sucks. everyone talks about how the accused‚Äôs life is ‚Äúover‚Äù, while ignoring that the accuser is potentially reliving traumas, suffering from ptsd (which occurs more highly in victims of sexual assault than military personal, fun fact), putting their reputation on the line, getting smeared and receiving death threats with little to no promise of justice in the end. only 1% of accused rapists go to jail in the states, another fun fact. so when you ask why we don‚Äôt come forward, why we bare our pain in silence, and why we band together so strongly when one of us is brave enough to come forward; keep in mind how deeply that type of pain resonates with so many of us. more of us than most men can actually imagine.
so as a fun reminder: if somebody says no, don‚Äôt pressure them. if somebody is passed out, they cannot consent. if somebody is clearly not in a good place mentally, don‚Äôt take advantage of them. and also, if your friend opens up and comes forward, be there for them. it‚Äôs not that hard to be a decent human being, y‚Äôall.
and as a note to any and all survivors: you‚Äôre valid. you aren‚Äôt just being dramatic. i believe you. ‚ù§

text:
we will not be silent anymore. 
thank you, dr. blasey ford, for exemplifying true patriotism and astounding courage in the face of the ugliest force in this country: full-throated patriarchal norms as perpetuated by misogynist, privileged white men who get belligerent when faced with the prospect of accountability. 
we owe you. we owe anita hill. and we will carry the torch from the path you burned.
love and strength, sisters. love and strength.

text:
this right here...what is happening in our country? what will continue to happen in the coming years? how far will government officials go to silence us? this is why i am now volunteering with a sexual assault and domestic violence advocacy center in central florida. it is why i have decided to pursue law school in 2021 after receiving my masters in public admin. in 2020. it is why i am pursuing a career as a voice for victims in this country and it is why i will work to bring change to our national administration, providing justice and an audience to victims and survivors of assault. it is why i will ensure that no one is silenced. i am bound by a conscious commitment to use my voice...it is something so strong within me that i cannot ignore it. and i choose to work harder in my life than i ever have before to ensure future generations don't know the fear so many of us are feeling now. in the words of kamala harris, i am going to be "at the table where decisions are made."

text:
#metoo

i don't usually ever keep up with politics. my general viewpoint is that it's all rigged and it's not in our favor.  but the events happening right now have been different. they bring up my own deep wounds, my own deep fears, and my own deep hopes for the future of this world.

women lost the battle today. men who have embraced their healthy masculinity lost the battle today. people, all of us, lost today. 
it feels like a losing battle. fighting for our right to be in control of our own bodies, fighting for our own sexuality, fighting to not be violated, fighting to be h e a r d.

but we must not stop fighting. 
we must keep telling our stories.

we must keep expressing our pain.

we must keep demanding a change.

we must keep standing tall and firm in our authenticity.

patriarchy keeps proving they won't listen. but we must keep proving we won't shut up.

i have been sexually abused by three different men. they were all men i trusted. they were all "good guys". i never reported any of them. 
but it still happened. 
my lack of reporting doesn't make it less real, less valid, or less traumatic. 
this is not a time to retreat. 
this is not a time to hide.

please, don't allow yourself to be defeated. 
this battle was lost. but the war continues.

your pain is your war cry. it's time to let that shit out louder than ever before.

#metoo #itsnotover #sexualabuse #whyididntreport #speakup #speakout #trauma #solidarity #sacredfeminine #sacredmasculine #sacredunion #wewillbeheard #goddess #risegoddessrise #kavanaugh

text:
i've loved and admired @ayannapressley since my first #barccwalk4change in 2013. seeing her speak is like seeing shakespeare as it was meant to be played, as sorkin would say. the only time i got choked up at monday's rally was standing by her side as she took the stage to speak. the idea of getting to stand behind her and look out on that crowd, after making my own speech, is more than a dream come true. i snuck a quick picture of the moment, my only goofy tourist moment on the dais. 
afterwards, a few kind folks made sure i got to speak to her - even though i've briefly met ayanna before, i've never gotten a picture. i wound up with her and ghe equally powerful alexandria ocasio-cortez, surrounded by reporters, and for once i was something approaching speechless. 
what i wanted to say is this: "we already have a perpetrator in chief, so why not a survivor in chief?" what i will never be able to fully express to her is what it has meant to hear her speak at the walk every year, a living beacon of healing, rage, honesty, and hope, and what it means to have her truly represent us, and carry our voices with her to the halls of power in washington dc. 
thank you, ayanna.

text:
i picked this up today at the bookstore. friends, i was shaking while i read the inside flap. atwoodian comparisons aside, i think vox will prove to be a poignant discussion of the resilience and unshakable strength found in women‚Äôs voices. i added in the orange stream shown here because we are igniting fiery justice together. know this: i hear you. your shouts and kicks and screams are your birthright.
.
.
.
‚Äúon the day the government decrees that women are no longer allowed more than one hundred words per day, dr. jean mcclellan is in denial. this can't happen here. not in america. not to her. soon women are not permitted to hold jobs. girls are not taught to read or write. females no longer have a voice. before, the average person spoke sixteen thousand words each day, but now women have only one hundred to make themselves heard. for herself, her daughter, and every woman silenced, jean will reclaim her voice. this is just the beginning...not the end.‚Äù
.
.
.

text: the entire us has been gripped by the kavanaugh hearing and we have just about come to the conclusion of what is sure to be seen as yet another sad truth about america: white supremacy and patriarchy still reign true and still have the power to steer those who proximally benefit into making decisions to protect the institution. there have been a lot of articles criticizing collins but i want to make it clear that that is veiled sexism. there were several swing voters and there is also a majority of men who voted to get kavanaugh confirmed, and yet we're focusing on one women's vote. it's definitely because we expect that she, as a woman, would be understanding and sympathetic to the statements by dr. ford. we expect collins to be able to shirk the influence of the party and make a decision that will inevitably earn her the disdain of all of her colleagues. we ask a lot because we deserve a lot, but i also think we need to ask the same of all those men in the room. partisanship in this country, especially for the republican party, who are actively promoting this idea that they are under attack when in actuality they are consistently in power (i.e. false victimhood for political and narrative control), is a symptom of a greater divide between the in group and the out group. we have reached a point where protecting the group has become so essential that we are willing to abandon the values that the group was founded on, or even personal morality and generativity. it's about power and protecting the seat of power. i know we are angry, but remember that there is only the privileged and those who have access by proxy. i have hope this will be a rallying point that shapes the course of us history, but i also wonder what we can do without radical action given the continuous manipulation of the system by power governors...

ü§¨
yesterday i felt like my life purpose was meaningless. but then i pulled this card. the nebula warrior uses the darkness of this planet to fight for a new consciousness. she is fearless, she creates her own rules, she does what needs to be done for freedom and liberation.
üí™üèº
whatever is going on in the world ‚Äî or in your own life ‚Äî can be healed. going for it directly can cause resistance so it‚Äôs best to get assistance and use the law of attraction. this way you can disempower negative influences and keep away the naysayers who only want to see you fail.
üôåüèª
the forces in this world that profit from fear and instead of love will try to confuse and overwhelm you so you begin to worry and stop taking action. be smart, fight smart, and never give up! you will win every war by being a warrior of love!

text:
following recent allegations by dr christine blasey ford that brett kavanaugh sexually assaulted her, the us republican judge has been confirmed to the supreme court, a position he will hold for life. the allegations came after the potus announced kavanaugh as his nomination. the fbi investigated the case and then released a report on the alleged sexual assault - after reading its contents, the us senate narrowly voted 50-48 in favour for trump's nominee. this means future rulings of the court will likely favour conservatism on contentious issues such as gun control and abortion. more importantly, the investigation prior to his confirmation has sparked controversy and protest on whether his character is fit to hold a place on the court, and has added to the #metoo movement. dr ford says kavanaugh attempted to rape her in 1982. many believe her, and many believe kavanaugh. despite this, he has still been confirmed. in my opinion, a person under investigation for such a serious incident should not have been appointed, unless the vote could have been extended due to exceptional circumstances, so that the senate could vote based on a more thorough investigation.
#brettkavanaugh #christineblaseyford #sexualassault #activism #politics #trump #supremecourt

text:
- this one always evokes strong emotions one way or the other. this is my opinion as a medical doctor, yogi, and also as a teacher/student navigating my way through the #metoo education period. 
this is what i teach my students and future teachers.  what you do and what you choose is entirely up to you. 
but i would ask myself these questions in regards to adjustments: 
what injury history has your teacher taken from you one on one?
what exam of your movements has your teacher taken? 
what anatomy and manipulation education has your teacher taken? 
what overseeing body has witnessed and licensed your teacher to perform adjustments? 
what insurance policy does your teacher carry and does it cover them if they injure you - or did you sign away that right with the waiver form? 
in today‚Äôs: strip mall yoga - teacher training mills- the answer to most of these questions is none. 
my recommendation: just say no to adjustments and make sure it is known at the beginning of class. 
all too often these days yoga teachers, who know nothing about you, think they can touch without asking.  so make it clear to avoid the awkward moment when they come to you in the middle of the pose and you either have to speak up disturbing the flow or allow them to do something you don‚Äôt want and didn‚Äôt ask for. 
#noadjustments #yogapsa

.
.
.
.

.

.
for those who are okay with this, are you really ok with our country being led by bullies, rapists, etc.? i understand if your views align with some of theirs, but ultimately, are you really okay with having people in elected office known for these heinous actions and every day behaviors? a specific example: those who birthed and raised children in the 70s and early 80‚Äôs - not the ‚Äúmillennials‚Äù and ‚Äúsnowflakes‚Äù you despise so much, but that in between generation? the ones who‚Äôs children put up with bullying and you fought so hard to change the tolerance of it? the ones who started to bring rape and assault to light to start the conversations that used to be taboo? we‚Äôve come so far from those starting points, and now so many of you have become so much more conservative now that your children are adults. how can you now be okay with this? what made you change those core basic moral human right beliefs?
.

.
my rage is not party specific. my rage is ignited because of monsters and terrible human beings being elected into office.

text:
on new year‚Äôs day of this year (2018) we drew a focus card for the coming year. that card was the star card.  that felt real nice when we drew it - hope is what we focus on - getting clear on what is truly good.  not to break the bad news after the good, but in the linear progression of the major arcana the tower comes right before the star.  well, we are seeing the tower rip sh*t down, all kinds of things are falling apart not the least of which is any sense of justice when the mendacious are put into places of the highest authority.  it‚Äôs a time for all the feels specifically outrage, sadness, anger etc.  it has to feel like this when this sh8t happens.  the country we thought we were living in (the usa) is crumbling. yuh.  shadows are coming at us rope-a-dope style as we are hit with the reality that there is way more darkness out there in the human ego than we wanted to admit (or at least me). that darkness is in the form of hate, fear, lies, denial, selfishness, greed, racism, misogyny...
.
and yet...
.
.
.
 i‚Äôd like to point us all back to the star at this moment in time.  that star is bright af and those shadows are being thrown into sharper and sharper relief every moment we focus on the good and the true.  another part of the potency of this stage is to draw us back to our guiding light -  the star we follow.  what we focus on will grow - and what happened today in the us with the confirmation of a man who is the epitome of patriarchal entitlement and  arrogance with a wicked case of shadow misogyny shows us that more needs to be done and on a person to person level which is the hardest f*ing work there is.  we have to share our light and refuse to let this knock us off our feet. so‚Ä¶
.
.
what is this star? i‚Äôll focus on the tragedy du jour and its relationship to women but this goes for all the worlds ills mentioned above. .
 what does the world look like when women actually control their own bodies, are recognized as equal and treated as such? where their choices matter, where we respect each other differences and all. what does it look like, sound like and feel like in a world where all of this is the reality for everyone. see next comment‚è©

that‚Äôs just called trauma. however, i am ashamed in the behavior of our society and the  systematic silencing of victims. this should not be about political strategy, this should be about basic human dignity.  we must do better. the future of our culture‚Äôs health demands it. we must take our anger and channel it into action. we must memorialize our tears as motivation. i am not ashamed to take today personally. #metoo #believesurvivors #sheisnotabandoned .

text:
late but here are the additions to my ink collection
edit: okay i didn't explain them but i forgot they do need an explanation. 
the last tattoo is 2 symbols put together. the top one (2 xs) is a greek symbol meaning "where there's a will, there's a way" the bottom half (2 arrows) is a viking symbol that means "create your own reality"
the second tattoo (the hand outlines-asl) spells out the word brave
the first tattoo is one i've wanted desperately since i first saw it, a fire rose unity survivor tattoo anyone who pays attention to @ladygaga may recognize it. i suggest giving her song "till it happens to you" a listen. the first tattoo comes from her, but it's meaning and importance to me, comes from my story. #metoo

honest and open conversation is the only way to move forward. link in bio.
