text:
as a survivor myself, if i could tell any survivor anything right now it's that your story matters regardless of any senate's reaction. the confirmation of kavanaugh literally cannot confirm our stories as survivors of sexual assault don't matter - because our experience will always inherently matter. no court ruling can weigh in on the validity of our experience.

did kav do it? i don't know. did the court rule fairly? i'll chose to trust so. either way - what this group of men decides literally has no bearing on how true my experience was and continues to be. it simply is, without their weighing in. our stories simply matter!

i survived the clergy sex abuse and am recovering every day! i came forward and told my church. i even told the pastor of the church who had recently hired the pastor who sexually abused me and he chose to keep him on staff. did that invalidate my story? no way. it's one man's reaction. my recovery happens regardless - that's our true power as survivors!

text:
cats against cat calls. but dangerous females definitely for this tee. another item for our auction (nov. 1st- save the date!) thanks jen from @fussygus. 
catcalling is not a compliment. it‚Äôs sexual harassment. catcalls are usually directed at women, but men get them too, they can be specifically targeted to people of colour and lgbtqia+ individuals and people with disabilities are also subjected to discriminatory language in public.
it‚Äôs a power play, if someone says something to you that can make you change direction, cross the street, re-think your clothing or just embarrass and shame you, then that‚Äôs their way of saying -i am in control of this environment. 
they can range from ‚Äúsmile beautiful‚Äù ‚Äúhey sexy‚Äù to ‚Äúshow me your tits‚Äù ‚Äúlift up your skirt‚Äù and worse.

text:
the fact that there was even a question that kavanaugh, a rapist, should be on the supreme court unfortunately doesn‚Äôt surprise me, but definitely enrages me. the fact that these people voted him in gives the message to sexual predators that they can live their lives consequence-free after ruining someone else‚Äôs. it gives the message to sexual assault and rape survivors that there‚Äôs no justice, no hope. i don‚Äôt know a single woman who doesn‚Äôt feel guilt or shame after traumatic event(s) like this happen. the burden always goes onto her, even though it isn‚Äôt her fault. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
when i came forward and brought my abuser to court, several people who didn‚Äôt even know me wrote about how i lied, how i was never abused, how my abuser never did anything to me, how he even ‚Äúloved‚Äù me and only wanted the best for me. every day i think about how he should be in jail. how he shouldn‚Äôt ever be allowed to come in contact with women or animals ever again. how his life should be ruined because of this, because he ruined a huge part of mine, and *doesn‚Äôt even show remorse*. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
i don‚Äôt know what to do with the information that a rapist is on the supreme court. i don‚Äôt know when all this bullshit will stop or how i can help. all i want to do is live my life but it seems like everywhere i turn, i can‚Äôt ignore what‚Äôs going on in this country. until the day when survivors are believed and rapists are held accountable, i‚Äôm just going to be here supporting those who need it. üíî #stopkavanaugh #kavanaughisarapist #metoo #ibelievesurvivors #ibelievechristineford #menaretrash #fucktrump

text:
**trigger warning** the first time i was raped was when i was 18. i didn‚Äôt report it because i didn‚Äôt want to hurt the camaraderie on our flight at work, and also i felt as though i wouldn‚Äôt be believed because i had been promiscuous in the past and i dressed a certain way. to this day, i still have a hard time naming the persons who did it. i have the utmost respect for the women who know they will be judged and still come forward. 
the thing is, we survivors of rape and sexual assault go on with our lives the best we can after it happens, and we try to forget it as much as possible. if you asked me details about that night, i wouldn‚Äôt be able to tell you much other than split seconds of flashbacks i remember clear as day, because i did my best to forget as much as i could about that night (i recently had to try to recount it for a counselor at the va last year and it really had me fucked up). we want to forget. 
i believe ms ford because she was 15 and at a party when she was assaulted and, like me, she probably wanted to forget as much as possible. i believe her because she has had nothing to gain from coming forward other than hate and backlash, yet she did so anyway because she felt the need to let people know the truth. she is courageous and strong for doing so, and i‚Äôm willing to bet she already knew he wasn‚Äôt going to be criminally prosecuted with no legal proof, since she‚Äôs an educated woman. she spoke out despite knowing justice cannot be done, because she felt the need to let people know the truth about the man who is being appointed to the highest court in the us. i believe her. 
i was too afraid to say something in my situation because of the backlash from a group of 30-40 people i worked with, but she spoke out knowing she was facing backlash from an entire country. something to think about. #metoo #fordvskavanaugh #strongwomen #zerotolerance #enoughisenough #timesup #ibelieveher #feminism

text:
silence.
he thought he had won
had found his solace...
for the silence mislead
to that high plateau
full of ego
and smug apathy
turned smug victory
granting ego 
miracle grow
he was blinded
so blinded by the growth
that he could not see
the rallying army
on the other side
of the silence
waiting
biding their time
once more

can't go back in time to change in someone's eyes that i was not something to play with
try not to talk about it, i'm too mad, i'm too late, i'm too gentle

text:
so it's done and i feel like this orb weaver hiding inside a curled leaf. but i'm trying to focus on my anger and not my fear. every single survivor has just been figuratively spat upon by our own government and quite literally told that they don't matter. i'm appalled and furious, but i'm also terrified and heartbroken. shame on every single person who voted to confirm such an unconscionably unsuitable candidate for a position on the #scotus. shame on every one of them who ignored the countless voices demanding that they simply do their job by representing the will of the people. shame on their laughable sham of an investigation. shame on their claims that "#metoo matters" while voting the opposite. we need to hang onto our rage and vote with it in november. votes to confirm today should equal seats lost come november. how else will they learn? why else should they care, since they clearly have no scruples or empathy? ‚Ä¢
and for those of you who are reeling from this news, just as i am: i see you. i hear you. i fucking believe you. and i'm holding space for you in my furious heart. üî•üñ§üî•

text:
emotions are running high. the universe  is suffering. collectively we‚Äôre united in our pain. old wounds have been ripped open. wounds that some believed had healed are now re-emerging as if they are fresh and brand new once again. whatever the trauma is, the pain is real. the memories we have, the impact that it‚Äôs had on us are the only evidence we need. we know our truths. we were witness to our own experiences and our own pains. the healing doesn‚Äôt come from having to prove anything to anyone. we know. that‚Äôs all that matters. someone else‚Äôs memory or lack there of doesn‚Äôt change what we know is true. the fact that old wounds can be ripped open doesn‚Äôt mean you haven‚Äôt done the work to move forward. it just means it‚Äôs time to explore how those wounds affect you today and it‚Äôs time to heal even deeper. the fact that our wounds are still so painful is a precious opportunity to continue our healing, in new and different ways from before. we are different now. we have evolved. we are stronger now and can use this time of collective suffering to support one another on our journeys of healing. if you are in touch with your feelings you know and deeply understand how all your experiences impact you personally. we can support one another but know that our own healing is an individual journey. no one can heal your pain for you. you have to be willing to allow the pain to emerge in order to process it and heal it. it‚Äôs time to be kind and gentle with yourself as you navigate your wounds and tenderly engage in active healing. your wounds don‚Äôt define you but they do help you build strengths. your wounds and your willingness to heal are powerful expressions of your resiliency. you are stronger than you know and you can get through whatever pain this is. you can heal and you can and will persevere ‚ù§Ô∏è
.
.

text:
in the gita, shiva shows himself to arjuna as the most beautiful arjuna had ever seen, and more grotesque than arjuna could handle looking at. reminding us good and bad does not exist, that what we think of as reality is only a hologram to push us toward what we must learn. that earth is a cauldron of suffering, and through this suffering we reach truth, and the ability to go to nirvana, or another blue planet with higher more evolved beings. to move past ego and remember we are in an iron age, a destructive fiery hot angry patriarchal age--that only through this can we reach the heart and then enlightenment both personally and universally. in yoga its not that god is "good", its that god is the only thing thats real, and so, shiva will show up in nasty disguises, like donald trump and brett kavanaugh to push us towards true compassion, empathy, truth and freedom. because without these iterations of shiva we would never get past ego, we would never get past the "human", and so humanity needs this moment (which has lasted since the dark ages and is not over yet, its over 1000's of years) to evolve into enlightenment. i know this is all true through meditation, however, the witch and the woman in me today are devastated and enraged, hopeless and helpless, ashamed of this country and sad to have to live through this. but i know the goddess is coming, and  this is how we find her again--through grostesque forms of shiva. without the catalyst there is no action. and also, fuck the patriarchy #feminist #fuckkavanaugh üê∫
.
.

‚Äúthe confirmation process has been bitterly partisan, and disputes were exacerbated by allegations of sexual misconduct against kavanaugh that began surfacing in september. in response to the allegations, the senate judiciary committee heard testimony from kavanaugh and christine blasey ford, who alleges kavanaugh sexually assaulted her when they were in high school. kavanaugh denies the allegation, while she has stood by her testimony.

the committee paused the nomination process for a week so the fbi could investigate. afterwards, republicans declared that the fbi had not found any corroborating witnesses, while democrats complained the fbi didn't look hard or long enough.

when is the senate vote on kavanaugh?
senators voted to advance kavanaugh's confirmation friday morning by a 51-49 margin.

the final senate vote was 50-48 margin in favor of confirming kavanaugh to the highest court. republican sen. steve daines of montana was not present at the vote because he was attending his daughter's wedding. republican sen. lisa murkowski of alaska, who broke with her party on friday and voted against advancing kavanaugh's nomination, voted "present."‚Äù

text:
i wish i could say ‚Äúwe will look back on this day and be shocked that such a thing ever came to pass‚Äù but i can‚Äôt say that - how can one responsibly say such a thing, after the last two years of #metoo, where speeches made onstage during large hollywood award shows were applauded publicly by the very men who, behind the scenes, assaulted, manipulated, & abused those with less power & less of a voice...time & time & time again. 
i wish i could say that @sensusancollins ‚Äúyes‚Äù vote shocked me. she is a woman. she should know better...right? she should be shamed by the mere concept of voting anything but no, no, & no. i can‚Äôt say that that shocked me. white women were responsible for trump‚Äôs rise to power. & now, white women are greatly responsible for kavanaugh‚Äôs placement in the supreme court. 
dr. christine blasey ford stood under oath & gave a testimony in an attempt to protect the women of this country. she had nothing to personally gain; she had much to personally lose...but she did it anyway. 
it‚Äôs no exaggeration to call this a dark & evil day. 
@mcconnellpress just said ‚Äúa vote to confirm judge kavanaugh today is a vote to end this brief, dark chapter in the senate‚Äôs history and turn the page toward a brighter tomorrow.‚Äù mitch mcconnell - shame on you. the supreme court seat is a lifetime appointment. women will be suffering for decades  because of the choice you & your colleagues made today. i will say that tomorrow will be brighter when you & the men & women who voted kavanaugh through are underground. but even when you‚Äôre gone, women will still be living in the ‚Äúbrighter tomorrow‚Äù which is not, in fact, bright at all. 
thank you to #christineblaseyford; thank you to #anitahill (we will not forget her); thank you to all the sexual assault survivors who spoke out these past weeks & months. the future is even more frightening now. let us please remember to use our voices. vote. vote. for the love of god, vote. #ibelieveher ~image via @whyididntreportit~

text:
i was almost gang raped at the age of 22. we all read about the story of the girl who drank too much at the party. that was me. 
it was new years eve. my friends and i went to a party in a nice hotel in the ritzy gold coast in chicago. i drank too much champagne and got sick. everyone left to go to the club, except me. i stayed behind in the bathroom. 
i was lying down when i saw the door open to the hotel room. a group of guys started coming in. i had a bad feeling and ran to the bathroom and held the door lock for dear life. they taunted me from behind the door as they tried to break it down and pick the lock. i was crying and screaming my head off as they laughed and told me what horrible things they planned to do. a security guard heard me. i thought he was going to help me. he wanted in on it. üò¢ i kept screaming. finally, he told them i was making too much noise and they left.

i can never explain well enough the sheer terror i felt. i was afraid to even open the door to make sure the coast was clear so i could escape. unless you know what it's like to have a human being prey on you like a pack of wolves, you will never understand. 20+ years later, it pains me even to write this. and i am one of the lucky ones who got away. my heart breaks for those who did not. i know way too many of them. üò¢
üíî
i would bet those pos all have families now. i would bet they would all lie and deny what they did.

time that passes is irrelevant. the scars last a lifetime. i am tired of women being vilified for speaking up. they are being violated and shamed again for trying to help others. no one wants to relive that horror. it never should have happened. these women are warriors. i applaud each and every one of you. ‚ù§

we will never be silenced!üí™
üïä

text:
the senate voted to confirm judge brett m. kavanaugh as the supreme court‚Äôs 114th justice on saturday by one of the narrowest margins in the institution‚Äôs history, as police stood guard and protesters‚Äô shouts of ‚Äúshame, shame‚Äù echoed through the senate chamber.
‚Ä¢
